{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3a7bd8ca-c1ab-42f4-9a31-daec3ba503c6","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n    {\n#if ANDROID\n        events.AddAndroid(android => android\n            .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on pause */ })\n            .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n        events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on background */ }));\n#endif\n    });\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional\n- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.\n- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.\n- Each callback receives the platform-native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a3a086a2-c6a6-48ba-8295-c6c645360351","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":406,"requestId":"3C3E:A0D2E:D22C48:10657BE:6A012985"},"id":"aee4f8b0-aca1-4ba0-b3fa-dfd7e08d6445","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:57:49.007Z","parentId":"57e55574-f79c-4017-ac9f-9837206c6b99"}
